<TABLE width="100%" cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0><TR><TD
    valign=top bgcolor="#990000"><IMG
    src="http://images.slashdot.org/slc.gif" width=13 height=16 alt="" align=top><FONT 
    size=4 color="#FFFFFF" face="arial,helvetica"><B>Unified BSD packaging system?</B></FONT></TD>
</TR></TABLE><A HREF="http://slashdot.org/search.pl?topic=links"><IMG SRC="http://images.slashdot.org/topics/quicklinks.gif" WIDTH="60" HEIGHT="60"
	BORDER="0" ALIGN="RIGHT" HSPACE="20" VSPACE="10" ALT="Links">
</A> <B>Posted by <A HREF="mailto:nik@slashdot.org">nik</A>  on  Sunday September 03, @12:20PM</B><BR>
<FONT size=2><B>from the Must-get-around-to-playing-with-apt-get dept.</B></FONT><BR>
<a href="mailto:chrisc@daemonnews.org">Chris Coleman</a> is putting his money where his mouth is, after his recent <a href="http://daily.daemonnews.org/view_story.php3?story_id=1128">suggestion that the BSDs need a unified package collection</a>.  The creation of <a href="http://www.openpackages.org/">www.openpackages.org</a> was the next logical step, and Chris discusses this in his <a href="http://www.daemonnews.org/200009/editorial.html">latest Daemon News editorial</a>.  With representatives from the three free BSD projects, as well as Apple (MacOS X) on board, this certainly has the potential to bring about closer ties between the BSD distributions at a level that will affect a lot of users.

